==English==

===Etymology===
Recorded since 1550, from {{etyl|frm|en}} [[plate-forme]], literally "flat form", from {{etyl|frm|en}} [[plate]] "flat" (from {{etyl|fro|en}} [[plat]], of uncertain origin) + [[forme]] "form" (from {{etyl|la|en}} [[forma]]). Compare {{term|flatscape|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-platform.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A raised [[stage]] from which [[speech]]es are made and on which musical and other [[performance]]s are made.
# A place or an opportunity to express one's opinion, a [[tribune]]
#: ''this new talk show will give a '''platform''' to everyday men and women''
# A kind of high [[shoe]] with an extra layer between the inner and outer soles
# {{context|figurative}} {{rfdef|lang=en}}
